{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"43c15aca-cd62-44c9-b08b-653beafe7845","content":"Let me also check for the packaging file (`.nuspec` or `.csproj`) and the template content.","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_BH5WVc1ONXQSZEseBU3geC","name":"view","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-30c860fd2feb4c78820d7d5514e98494"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"view the file at /tmp/sv-30c860fd2feb4c78820d7d5514e98494."},{"toolCallId":"tooluse_nCOFS395AjiJzZe5sQ6GFx","name":"glob","arguments":{"pattern":"**/*.{nuspec,csproj,nupkg}","path":"/tmp/sv-30c860fd2feb4c78820d7d5514e98494"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"/tmp/sv-30c860fd2feb4c78820d7d5514e98494"}],"interactionId":"b6cfde99-d441-44c0-a93a-09d67dfe98b5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check against the .NET template engine schema requirements.\n\nIssues I can spot:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not strictly required, but strongly recommended for validation and editor support.\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet packages so templates can be grouped.\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Useful when multiple versions of a template exist.\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Common best practice.\n5. **`defaultValue: \"net9.0\"`** — The default value should match one of the choice keys. It does (\"net9.0\" is a valid choice), so that's fine.\n\n\n6. **`Framework` symbol needs a `replaces` property** — Without it, the parameter won't actually substitute anything in the generated files. This is critical if the framework version needs to be injected into the `.csproj` or other source files, though I'd need to see the full template structure to confirm whether it's being used through conditional directives or other mechanisms.\n\nNow I'm looking at the broader template configuration issues: the template.json is missing a `$schema` declaration for editor support, lacks a `groupIdentity` field which is important for